  <p><a href="/providers/safetywing">Read our full SafetyWing review</a></p>

  <h2 id="how-it-works">How Catastrophic Insurance Works</h2>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns2} rows={comparisonRows2} />
  </div>

  <h3>The Math</h3>
  <p>
    Understanding the trade-off:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive plan:</strong> $500/month = $6,000/year in premiums</li>
    <li><strong>Catastrophic plan:</strong> $150/month = $1,800/year in premiums</li>
    <li><strong>Savings:</strong> $4,200/year</li>
    <li><strong>Your risk:</strong> $5,000 deductible</li>
    <li><strong>Net:</strong> Even if you hit your deductible, you save money</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>When It Makes Sense</h3>
  <p>
    Catastrophic coverage works when:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>You're healthy and rarely use healthcare</li>
    <li>You can afford to pay the deductible if needed</li>
    <li>You'd rather save on premiums</li>
    <li>You have emergency savings</li>
    <li>Your expected healthcare costs are low</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>When It Doesn't Make Sense</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>You have chronic conditions requiring regular care</li>
    <li>You expect to use healthcare frequently</li>
    <li>You can't afford a large unexpected expense</li>
    <li>You have young children (frequent doctor visits)</li>
    <li>You prefer predictable costs</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The Emergency Fund Requirement</h3>
  <p>
    Critical consideration:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep deductible amount in accessible savings</li>
    <li>$5,000 deductible = $5,000 emergency fund minimum</li>
    <li>Must be available immediately if needed</li>
    <li>Don't choose high deductible without this cushion</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Calculate Your Savings"
    description="See how much you could save with catastrophic coverage."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/compare/"
  />

  <h2 id="who-should-consider">Who Should Consider Catastrophic Insurance</h2>

  <h3>Ideal Candidates</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Young, healthy adults:</strong> Low expected healthcare use</li>
    <li><strong>Self-employed with savings:</strong> Can handle deductible, need low premiums</li>
    <li><strong>Digital nomads:</strong> Want protection without high ongoing costs</li>
    <li><strong>Early retirees:</strong> Bridge coverage with cost control</li>
    <li><strong>Those with local coverage:</strong> Supplement for international emergencies</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Not Recommended For</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Families with young children:</strong> Kids get sick frequently</li>
    <li><strong>Those with chronic conditions:</strong> Regular care exceeds savings</li>
    <li><strong>Pregnant or planning pregnancy:</strong> Maternity care is expensive</li>
    <li><strong>Older adults:</strong> Healthcare needs increase with age</li>
    <li><strong>Those without emergency savings:</strong> Can't afford deductible</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Strategies for Using Catastrophic Coverage</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Health savings:</strong> Put premium savings into emergency fund</li>
    <li><strong>Preventive focus:</strong> Invest in wellness to avoid major issues</li>
    <li><strong>Negotiate cash pay:</strong> Many providers offer discounts for cash</li>
    <li><strong>Use local options:</strong> Routine care may be cheap locally</li>
    <li><strong>Annual review:</strong> Reassess as health/life situation changes</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Catastrophic + Local Care</h3>
  <p>
    A popular combination:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Catastrophic international plan for major expenses</li>
    <li>Pay cash for routine local care (often cheap abroad)</li>
    <li>Best of both: protection + low ongoing costs</li>
    <li>Works well in countries with affordable healthcare</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>What's the difference between catastrophic and high-deductible insurance?</h3>
  <p>
    They're essentially the same thing. "Catastrophic" emphasizes protection against major expenses. "High-deductible" describes the mechanism. Both mean you pay more out-of-pocket before insurance kicks in, in exchange for lower premiums.
  </p>

  <h3>How high should my deductible be?</h3>
  <p>
    Choose a deductible you could comfortably pay from savings. $2,500-5,000 is common for moderate savings. $10,000 maximizes premium savings but requires substantial reserves. Don't choose a deductible you can't afford.
  </p>

  <h3>Does catastrophic insurance cover preventive care?</h3>
  <p>
    Varies by plan. Some include preventive care before deductible (like US ACA plans). Most international catastrophic plans apply deductible to everything. Check specific plan terms.
  </p>

  <h3>What counts toward my deductible?</h3>
  <p>
    Usually all covered medical expenses: doctor visits, prescriptions, tests, hospital care. Once you've paid the deductible amount, insurance covers remaining costs (subject to any coinsurance).
  </p>

  <h3>Can I switch from catastrophic to comprehensive later?</h3>
  <p>
    Usually yes, at renewal. You may face new underwriting, waiting periods, or pre-existing condition exclusions. It's easier to switch than starting a new policy, but not automatic.
  </p>

  <h3>Is catastrophic insurance accepted for visa requirements?</h3>
  <p>
    Check specific visa requirements. Some countries require minimum coverage levels that catastrophic plans meet. Others may require comprehensive coverage. Verify before relying on catastrophic insurance for visa purposes.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This content is for informational purposes only. Catastrophic coverage requires financial planning. We are not insurance brokers or financial advisors. Verify coverage directly with insurers.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
